WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:02.520
Hello everyone. Let's get the session started.

2
00:00:03.100 --> 00:00:06.340
Welcome to this session, and this session is entitled

3
00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:10.710
"Claudin-Targeted Therapies from Tight Junction Biology to Next-Generation

4
00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:13.220
Precision Oncologies." I am Kohei Setara.

5
00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:17.160
I'm a German oncologist from Japan, and it is my great pleasure to

6
00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:20.380
be here with two distinguished speakers, Dr.

7
00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:24.460
Samuel Klempner from the United States and Dr. Lin Chen from China.

8
00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:28.820
So today, we're going to discuss several aspects of claudin-targeted therapy.

9
00:00:29.330 --> 00:00:32.980
Why is claudin targetable? What does this teach us

10
00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:36.720
about new category of precision oncology, and what are

11
00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:40.500
major challenges and limitation we must address before

12
00:00:40.540 --> 00:00:44.320
moving forward? So first, I will introduce some biological

13
00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.800
background and review how this biology is

14
00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:49.960
translated into clinical validation.

15
00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:54.100
Then following two speakers will introduce emerging and newer

16
00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:57.940
claudin-targeted therapy. And please scan this QR

17
00:00:58.260 --> 00:00:59.260
code and

18
00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:04.261
post any question and comment during the session, or please go to

19
00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:08.320
microphone to ask any question after each talk or during

20
00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:09.680
discussions section.

21
00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:12.680
So let me start my presentation.

22
00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:17.760
So here are my disclosures.

23
00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:20.700
So,

24
00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:25.500
as everyone know, current, our main target is oncogenic

25
00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:26.080
driver,

26
00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:29.200
because tumors are dependent on them.

27
00:01:29.580 --> 00:01:33.070
We can target EGFR mutation, ALK fusion, BRAF

28
00:01:33.100 --> 00:01:36.840
V600E mutation, and now KRAS, as well as the HER2

29
00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.780
amplification, because tumors are dependent on them.

30
00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:43.660
And when we hit, tumor shrink

31
00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:44.530
dramatically.

32
00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:49.230
In contrast, non-oncogenic target like claudin 18.2 is

33
00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:52.600
totally different. It is not essential for tumor cell

34
00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:55.900
proliferation, and tumors are not dependent on them.

35
00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:00.520
Instead, it is targetable because of lineage identity

36
00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:04.760
and tumor architecture. This represent a conceptual shift

37
00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:08.640
from targeting oncogenic addiction to targeting the

38
00:02:08.700 --> 00:02:11.160
architectural vulnerability within the tumors.

39
00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.380
Claudin 18.2 is a tight junction protein

40
00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.510
with lineage-restricted and differentiation-locked characteristics.

41
00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:25.000
It is usually located at the apical site of tight junction complex

42
00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:28.880
in normal gastric epithelium and hidden from circulating

43
00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.700
antibody. But during malignant transformation to gastric cancer,

44
00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:36.960
it is exposed to the tumor cell surface with disruption

45
00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.970
tight junction and loss of epithelial polarity,

46
00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:41.760
and

47
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:45.980
it could be targetable and accessible target.

48
00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:50.540
Of note, this expression exposure doesn't always mean

49
00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:52.600
overexpression by gene amplification.

50
00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:56.500
Rather, it is spatial redistribution that create

51
00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:57.940
this accessibility.

52
00:02:58.960 --> 00:02:59.880
So change of tumor

53
00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:04.700
architecture result in tumor vulnerability, which

54
00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:08.380
enables therapeutic targeting by antibody-based

55
00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:08.920
treatment.

56
00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:14.160
Claudin was actually discovered by Professor Tsukita and

57
00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:17.820
Furuse in Japan more than 20 years ago as a

58
00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:21.700
component of tight junction. The name claudin derived

59
00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:24.820
from Latin claudere, meaning to close.

60
00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:29.460
So initial idea is to understand the molecular biology of

61
00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:33.480
tight junction, but this biology eventually achieved

62
00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:34.660
therapeutic targeting

63
00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:36.520
decades later.

64
00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:41.900
To date, more than 20 members of claudin family have been

65
00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:45.640
identified, and each of them has unique barrier

66
00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:48.040
function and tissue distribution.

67
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.660
Claudin 18 has two isoforms, 18.1 in lung and

68
00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:57.460
18.2 in stomach. They differ by only seven

69
00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:01.360
amino acid in first extracellular loop, but this small

70
00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:04.860
difference is enough to achieve selective targeting by

71
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
antibody-based therapy without cross-reaction.

72
00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:12.600
And claudin 18.2 is so unique because its expression is

73
00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:16.120
entirely restricted in normal gastric epithelium.

74
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.860
Functionally, claudin 18.2 forms acid-resistant

75
00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:23.100
tight junction strand

76
00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:27.780
and maintain tissue integrity. A knockout mouse model of

77
00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:31.400
claudin 18.2 result in severe tissue damage by

78
00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:32.940
acid and gastritis.

79
00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:37.450
In clinical sample from patient with severe atrophic gastritis or

80
00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:41.160
intestinal metaplasia show the reaction of claudin expression.

81
00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:45.540
So understanding function of claudin 18.2 is somehow helpful

82
00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:49.160
for us to expect possible toxicity, like

83
00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.260
gastritis, by targeted agent.

84
00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:56.730
Claudin 18.2 targeted therapy was initially developed by Professor

85
00:04:56.820 --> 00:04:59.720
Tschiemann and Turci in Gan and Der Company in Germany.

86
00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:04.220
They found that claudin 18.2 is retained and membrane

87
00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.980
localized in gastric cancer, which is essential as a therapeutic

88
00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:11.580
target. So claudin 18.2 is commonly

89
00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:14.900
expressed in gastric and GI cancer, but it is also

90
00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:18.900
ectopically expressed in pancreas cancer or other types of

91
00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:21.640
tumor like mucinous type of ovarian cancers.

92
00:05:23.080 --> 00:05:26.600
The distribution of claudin 18.2 in gastric cancer has a

93
00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:30.560
U-shaped pattern. Around 30% showed a

94
00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:34.440
loss of claudin expression, and another 30% showed lower

95
00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:36.240
heterogeneous claudin expression.

96
00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:40.520
The remaining 40% showed high and homogeneous expression

97
00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:41.120
of claudin.

98
00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:46.020
Of note, these researches usually applied claudin 18 specific,

99
00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:50.160
claudin 18 diagnostic antibody, which can recognize both

100
00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:53.640
18.1 and 18.2 because binding site is

101
00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:57.540
intracellular common domain between 18.1 and 18.2,

102
00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:01.680
and different from therapeutic antibody like doraptaxumab, which bind

103
00:06:01.740 --> 00:06:04.880
first extracellular loop, which specific to

104
00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:08.660
18.2. But 18.1 expression in gastric

105
00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:12.260
cancer or stomach tissue is quite low or rare, so 18

106
00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:16.200
expression has been considered as equal to 18.2

107
00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:20.060
expression. But recent clinical trial applied more specific

108
00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:22.580
18.2 diagnostic antibody like

109
00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:26.596
SP455.Claudin and ARID fusion is

110
00:06:26.676 --> 00:06:30.656
also detected in less than 5% of gastric cancer, which is enriched in

111
00:06:30.716 --> 00:06:33.776
genomically stable type by TCGA classification.

112
00:06:34.136 --> 00:06:37.996
And this fusion lead to tumor invasiveness or aggressive phenotype

113
00:06:38.056 --> 00:06:41.336
because of loss of a binding site of claudin and

114
00:06:41.536 --> 00:06:43.256
dysregulation of a lower pathway.

115
00:06:43.516 --> 00:06:47.156
So tumor with claudin fusion usually maintain high expression of

116
00:06:47.236 --> 00:06:49.836
claudin fusion, but its function is impaired.

117
00:06:50.216 --> 00:06:53.696
Nevertheless, it could be targetable by antibody-based treatment

118
00:06:54.056 --> 00:06:57.915
because of its high expression. On the other hand, a tumor with claudin

119
00:06:58.036 --> 00:07:01.596
expression do not always show claudin fusion because fusion is a

120
00:07:01.656 --> 00:07:02.816
relatively rare event.

121
00:07:04.116 --> 00:07:07.916
Clinical pathological feature of claudin positive patient were also

122
00:07:08.096 --> 00:07:11.836
reported. We summarize the screening result during a phase three

123
00:07:11.916 --> 00:07:15.476
trial of sorafenib, including more than 4,000 patient,

124
00:07:15.836 --> 00:07:19.356
and identified 38% patient with claudin

125
00:07:19.416 --> 00:07:22.896
positivity defined as moderate to strong expression in

126
00:07:22.936 --> 00:07:26.776
75% of tumor cells. And there's a trend of a higher

127
00:07:26.856 --> 00:07:30.836
positivity in tumor with diffused histology than intestinal or young

128
00:07:30.896 --> 00:07:34.096
age than elderly, but actual difference was relatively small.

129
00:07:34.296 --> 00:07:37.956
So at least we can say that claudin can be detected in any clinical

130
00:07:37.996 --> 00:07:41.956
subtypes in gastric cancer. And these are actual my patient with

131
00:07:42.036 --> 00:07:45.756
very high claudin expression with various molecular phenotype

132
00:07:45.776 --> 00:07:49.376
like claudin fusion, EBB positive, HER2 positive, and a

133
00:07:49.416 --> 00:07:52.996
deficient MML. So claudin can be detected across

134
00:07:53.036 --> 00:07:56.836
molecular subgroup, and it suggests claudin

135
00:07:56.896 --> 00:08:00.796
defined lineage-based phenotype rather than phenotype based

136
00:08:00.856 --> 00:08:02.156
on molecular alteration.

137
00:08:04.876 --> 00:08:08.016
Spatial heterogeneity of claudin expression was also assessed.

138
00:08:08.256 --> 00:08:12.226
There's a relatively high concordance between primary tumor and regional lymph node

139
00:08:12.276 --> 00:08:15.656
metastasis, but there is some reports showing

140
00:08:16.096 --> 00:08:19.996
reduced expression claudin in peritoneal metastasis, possibly

141
00:08:20.076 --> 00:08:23.636
due to some mechanism like EMT. Also, we need additional

142
00:08:23.676 --> 00:08:24.896
research to clarify.

143
00:08:25.976 --> 00:08:29.156
Temporal heterogeneity of claudin expression was also reported.

144
00:08:29.516 --> 00:08:33.356
These four study showed around 40% patient or

145
00:08:33.456 --> 00:08:37.297
tumor with reduced claudin expression even after conventional cytotoxic

146
00:08:37.336 --> 00:08:41.236
chemotherapy. On the other hand, gain of claudin seem to be rare

147
00:08:41.297 --> 00:08:41.677
event.

148
00:08:42.536 --> 00:08:46.076
So this kind of lineage shift might be important for us to consider

149
00:08:46.116 --> 00:08:49.956
appropriate timing to use claudin-targeted therapy or sequence of

150
00:08:50.056 --> 00:08:51.096
treatment.

151
00:08:51.956 --> 00:08:55.816
Immunological profile of claudin positive patient was also compared with that

152
00:08:55.836 --> 00:08:59.826
of claudin negative. We reported high infiltration of macrophage

153
00:08:59.876 --> 00:09:03.676
in claudin positive than negative, but same was not true in similar study from

154
00:09:03.776 --> 00:09:07.576
China applying different cutoff level of claudin, and it showed

155
00:09:07.736 --> 00:09:11.576
more exhausted CD8 T cell infiltration claudin positive tumors.

156
00:09:12.216 --> 00:09:16.056
I believe this kind of discordance might be based on a different

157
00:09:16.156 --> 00:09:20.016
molecular profile of each claudin positive patient as very heterogeneous

158
00:09:20.536 --> 00:09:21.876
tumors. But

159
00:09:22.936 --> 00:09:26.736
immuno profile or immuno context of each patient must be important for us

160
00:09:26.816 --> 00:09:30.796
for selecting appropriate claudin-targeted modality in the very near futures.

161
00:09:31.926 --> 00:09:35.516
And the interaction of claudin and other immuno cells are also

162
00:09:35.556 --> 00:09:39.296
reported. This interesting study suggest interaction between claudin

163
00:09:39.376 --> 00:09:42.176
positive tumor and cancer-associated fibroblast.

164
00:09:42.526 --> 00:09:46.346
Claudin enhance the adhesion between tumor cells and cancer-associated

165
00:09:46.476 --> 00:09:49.805
fibroblast, which result in tumor cell clustering and

166
00:09:49.876 --> 00:09:53.656
infiltration, and claudin-targeted agent disrupt this interaction.

167
00:09:54.476 --> 00:09:57.996
In a very recent interesting study published in "Science

168
00:09:58.036 --> 00:10:01.916
Immunology" also show the interaction between claudin positive tumor

169
00:10:02.036 --> 00:10:05.596
and myeloid cells. Claudin acts like a immuno checkpoint

170
00:10:05.636 --> 00:10:08.956
ligand in myeloid cell to activate immunosuppressive

171
00:10:09.056 --> 00:10:12.836
activity of macrophages, and the disruptome

172
00:10:13.036 --> 00:10:16.656
of this interaction increase anti-tumor immunity.

173
00:10:17.236 --> 00:10:21.076
So claudin-targeted agent show not only cytotoxic activity but

174
00:10:21.136 --> 00:10:23.316
also moderation of tumor microenvironment.

175
00:10:24.196 --> 00:10:26.696
So let's move on to claudin-targeted treatment.

176
00:10:27.036 --> 00:10:30.836
Zorvotaximab is a first-in-class IgG monoclonal antibody against claudin

177
00:10:30.876 --> 00:10:34.836
18.2, which has minimal signal blockade activity since

178
00:10:34.896 --> 00:10:38.895
claudin is not oncogenic driver. But it can induce strong

179
00:10:39.016 --> 00:10:42.296
ADCC and CDC reaction as main mode of action.

180
00:10:43.115 --> 00:10:47.076
Zorvotaximab monotherapy showed modest single agent activity with response

181
00:10:47.156 --> 00:10:50.656
rate of less than 10%, even in biomarker-enriched population.

182
00:10:51.096 --> 00:10:55.036
But around 30% to 40% patient achieved a stable disease as a main

183
00:10:55.136 --> 00:10:58.736
efficacy aspect. And on target GI toxicity are commonly

184
00:10:58.796 --> 00:11:01.816
observed in patient without previous gastrectomy.

185
00:11:02.266 --> 00:11:05.836
In a subsequent randomized phase two FASTO study suggest improved

186
00:11:05.976 --> 00:11:08.056
PFS with fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy.

187
00:11:08.556 --> 00:11:12.456
And then two global phase three studies confirmed the survival benefit of

188
00:11:12.496 --> 00:11:15.936
Zorvu plus fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy, which lead to regulatory

189
00:11:16.016 --> 00:11:19.856
approval of this combination in multiple countries.

190
00:11:19.896 --> 00:11:23.656
On target GI toxicity such as nausea, vomiting, and epigastric

191
00:11:23.716 --> 00:11:27.686
pain are commonly observed, especially during first administration,

192
00:11:27.976 --> 00:11:30.876
and the instance was decreased at subsequent cycle.

193
00:11:32.016 --> 00:11:35.956
And if we do endoscopy, this kind of gastritis or tissue damage are also

194
00:11:36.056 --> 00:11:38.896
commonly observed. And the preclinical study suggest

195
00:11:38.996 --> 00:11:42.816
complement-dependent cytotoxicity or CDC as main mode of

196
00:11:42.916 --> 00:11:45.156
action to induce this GI toxicity.

197
00:11:45.936 --> 00:11:49.876
So these events are relatively transient, and most of the patient could continue

198
00:11:49.916 --> 00:11:51.876
treatment without discontinuation.

199
00:11:52.316 --> 00:11:55.736
However, still this is somehow tricky or challenging to

200
00:11:55.816 --> 00:11:59.536
apply this into clinical practice because it require multiple

201
00:11:59.576 --> 00:12:03.196
antiemetics and long infusion and infusion adjustment.

202
00:12:03.696 --> 00:12:07.496
And also it is somehow expected because claudin is usually

203
00:12:07.536 --> 00:12:11.436
hidden within tight junction. But this toxicity suggest at least a

204
00:12:11.476 --> 00:12:15.466
transient exposure of therapeutic antibody even in

205
00:12:15.476 --> 00:12:16.336
normal tissue.

206
00:12:17.176 --> 00:12:21.016
And actually, more and more recent newer claudin-targeted

207
00:12:21.216 --> 00:12:24.036
agents still show some range of GI toxicity.

208
00:12:24.116 --> 00:12:28.016
So this is one of the challenging aspect of this class of agent, and

209
00:12:28.076 --> 00:12:31.712
we need to improve therapeutic index.And next, the

210
00:12:31.732 --> 00:12:35.232
pancreas cancer showed a different outcome or contrast.

211
00:12:35.692 --> 00:12:39.262
In random phase 2 study of cerpituximab plus fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy,

212
00:12:39.812 --> 00:12:43.472
28% of patients were diagnosed as claudin positivity with the same

213
00:12:43.532 --> 00:12:47.332
criteria with gastric cancer. However, the overall survival as a

214
00:12:47.432 --> 00:12:49.732
primary endpoint was not improved.

215
00:12:50.512 --> 00:12:54.452
Although the detail of the study result have not yet been reported, this

216
00:12:54.492 --> 00:12:56.992
suggests expression alone may not be enough.

217
00:12:58.552 --> 00:13:02.312
In gastric cancer, this is a lineage-restricted expression.

218
00:13:02.732 --> 00:13:06.592
In pancreas cancer, this is a more ectopic expression, so subcellular

219
00:13:06.652 --> 00:13:08.452
localization might be different.

220
00:13:08.992 --> 00:13:12.652
And actually, recent emerging data suggest KRAS

221
00:13:12.661 --> 00:13:15.852
mutations are associated with more cytoplasmic

222
00:13:15.932 --> 00:13:19.912
accumulation of claudin 18.2, which could be

223
00:13:20.532 --> 00:13:24.412
one of the possible explanations of limited activity of

224
00:13:24.452 --> 00:13:27.432
cerpituximab in pancreas cancer, even with

225
00:13:27.852 --> 00:13:29.912
immunochemistry positive staining.

226
00:13:30.692 --> 00:13:34.432
Although we need actual study results to interpret, but not only

227
00:13:34.472 --> 00:13:38.452
expression, but also other aspects like localization,

228
00:13:38.552 --> 00:13:42.492
immuno context, and tumor microenvironment might be important to predict

229
00:13:42.512 --> 00:13:44.552
the activity of claudin-targeted therapy.

230
00:13:45.652 --> 00:13:49.252
On the other hand, cerpituximab modulate tumor microenvironment.

231
00:13:49.652 --> 00:13:53.272
We collect a tumor sample before and after cerpituximab

232
00:13:54.092 --> 00:13:57.422
during phase one study as monotherapy, and it showed increased

233
00:13:57.452 --> 00:14:01.352
infiltration of AFC gamma positive NDK cells and macrophages, as

234
00:14:01.372 --> 00:14:05.172
well as increase of several chemokines, which eventually induce T cell

235
00:14:05.212 --> 00:14:09.052
infiltration. And I think these are helpful

236
00:14:09.132 --> 00:14:12.272
information to consider combination with checkpoint inhibitors.

237
00:14:13.512 --> 00:14:17.152
In also our additional preclinical studies suggest ADCP to

238
00:14:17.192 --> 00:14:21.012
induce phagocytosis as another important mode of action of

239
00:14:21.052 --> 00:14:24.952
cerpituximab, which was not well described previously.

240
00:14:24.962 --> 00:14:28.772
And interestingly, this ADCP activity was not diminished by the

241
00:14:28.812 --> 00:14:30.712
concurrent use of a corticosteroid.

242
00:14:31.352 --> 00:14:34.812
In clinical trials of cerpituximab, use of steroid was not

243
00:14:34.932 --> 00:14:38.872
recommended because of preclinical concern to diminish ADCC

244
00:14:39.112 --> 00:14:43.092
activity. However, exploratory analysis of phase three suggests the

245
00:14:43.152 --> 00:14:45.932
more benefit of cerpituximab in patients receiving

246
00:14:46.532 --> 00:14:50.432
pre-medication with steroid with better tolerability, which is in line

247
00:14:50.472 --> 00:14:53.632
with ADCP as an important mode of action.

248
00:14:55.492 --> 00:14:59.372
In vivo study also confirmed the combination activity with ZOLPI plus

249
00:14:59.382 --> 00:15:03.272
checkpoint inhibitor and chemotherapy, and this seemed to be better than two-drug

250
00:15:03.332 --> 00:15:07.312
combination with ZOLPI plus chemo or a checkpoint inhibitor plus chemotherapy.

251
00:15:07.952 --> 00:15:11.932
And based on this rationale, we have conducted a phase two trial to test

252
00:15:12.032 --> 00:15:15.852
combination with ZOLPI, chemotherapy, and checkpoint inhibitor, and

253
00:15:15.912 --> 00:15:17.502
it showed encouraging activity,

254
00:15:18.612 --> 00:15:22.332
in terms of PFS and response rate, especially in patients with high claudin

255
00:15:22.372 --> 00:15:26.272
expression and PDL1 FPS1 or greater, and currently phase

256
00:15:26.292 --> 00:15:29.632
three Luciana study is going to confirm these findings.

257
00:15:30.672 --> 00:15:34.492
And previously I mentioned the change of claudin expression before and after

258
00:15:34.572 --> 00:15:38.552
cytotoxic chemotherapy. We also summarize the claudin change before and

259
00:15:38.652 --> 00:15:42.292
after chemo plus cerpituximab, and around half of patients

260
00:15:42.392 --> 00:15:46.132
maintain claudin expression, but the other half of patients showed reduced

261
00:15:46.252 --> 00:15:49.992
claudin expression, although some of these patients still maintain low

262
00:15:50.032 --> 00:15:53.432
level of claudin expression. So to eradicate all

263
00:15:53.452 --> 00:15:57.332
claudin-positive tumor cells and to prevent lineage shift,

264
00:15:57.472 --> 00:16:00.152
we may need more active claudin-targeted treatment.

265
00:16:01.272 --> 00:16:05.192
And actually, more than 30 agents have been tested in clinical trials, and

266
00:16:05.292 --> 00:16:08.752
I believe most of these agents will be covered in following presentation.

267
00:16:09.112 --> 00:16:12.352
But here I just want to say, selecting appropriate

268
00:16:12.412 --> 00:16:16.092
claudin-targeted modality shouldn't be based on target

269
00:16:16.172 --> 00:16:20.152
expression alone, but we need to consider other aspects like internalization

270
00:16:20.232 --> 00:16:23.742
kinetics, architectural or immuno context, and tumor

271
00:16:23.772 --> 00:16:24.672
microenvironment.

272
00:16:25.712 --> 00:16:29.592
So future biomarker analysis for precision therapy should

273
00:16:30.272 --> 00:16:34.252
include not only target expression by immunohistochemistry, but also

274
00:16:34.312 --> 00:16:38.292
more architectural analysis by spatial transcriptome, multiplex

275
00:16:38.372 --> 00:16:42.132
immunohistochemistry, or newer types of emerging modality to

276
00:16:42.192 --> 00:16:44.672
stratify patients into right treatment.

277
00:16:46.052 --> 00:16:49.692
And lastly, this kind of experience of claudin 18.2

278
00:16:49.752 --> 00:16:53.722
targeted development could be applied for other lineage-based

279
00:16:53.872 --> 00:16:57.492
therapy or other claudin family. Claudin six is a

280
00:16:57.552 --> 00:17:01.272
reactivated oncofetal protein, which is not expressed

281
00:17:01.332 --> 00:17:05.312
in any of the normal tissue, but it is expressed in various

282
00:17:05.373 --> 00:17:08.992
types of tumors, like testicular cancer, ovarian cancer,

283
00:17:09.232 --> 00:17:13.072
and GI cancer. And multiple claudin six-targeted agents showed

284
00:17:13.113 --> 00:17:15.652
preliminary activity in early clinical studies.

285
00:17:16.272 --> 00:17:20.072
And claudin, other targeted agent for other claudin family

286
00:17:20.133 --> 00:17:23.772
is also investigated, but mostly at preclinical stage.

287
00:17:25.232 --> 00:17:28.892
So in summary, claudin 18.2 is a unique target with

288
00:17:29.212 --> 00:17:32.832
lineage-restricted and differentiation locked characteristic.

289
00:17:34.192 --> 00:17:38.032
It could be targetable because of disruption of tight junction and

290
00:17:38.132 --> 00:17:42.092
loss of epithelial polarity, which result in more exposure of

291
00:17:42.192 --> 00:17:45.532
therapeutic agent in tumors compared with normal tissues.

292
00:17:46.272 --> 00:17:49.992
Of note, this is not overexpression, but architectural

293
00:17:50.372 --> 00:17:53.972
change or architectural vulnerability in tumors, and it

294
00:17:54.072 --> 00:17:57.572
achieved more exposure. And understanding this architectural

295
00:17:57.632 --> 00:18:01.362
vulnerability in tumor, we may open the new category of precision

296
00:18:01.372 --> 00:18:04.132
oncology. With that, I would like to finish my talk.

